							<div class="rowTxt">
							
							
							
								<p class="newsHead">Civil court fees set to rise</p>
								<p class="newsDate">Jul&nbsp;2009</p>
								<p>Professional Support Lawyer with Optima Legal, Chris Taylor, said that in some cases, charges were due to rise to almost three times current rates as the courts attempted to recoup their administration costs. <br /><br />“We’ve sent our clients a full summary of the anticipated fee increases, which will come into force on 13 July,” said Chris. “They range from an extra £15 on a request for the issue of a default costs certificate, bringing the cost to £60, to an almost doubling of the cost for an application for a charging order, taking it from £55 to £100. Requests for bailiffs to attend county court for questioning will more than triple from £30 to £100.”<br /><br />The new fee increases will undoubtedly have a knock on effect on how cases are pursued through the courts. Optima Legal, one of only three law firms which responded to the Ministry of Justice consultation on the changes, pointed out a number of difficulties which would be faced by creditors as a result of the increases.<br /><br />Chris continues “The fee for sealing a writ of execution in the High Court will remain at £50. This is likely to make enforcement through the High Court more attractive, given the efficient and robust service offered by High Court Enforcement Officers.<br /><br />“Also, under the new fee structure for county courts, it will cost £100 to enforce a debt of £125, compared to an existing fee of £35. The Ministry of Justice justifies this on the basis that the administrative cost to the court is the same for all applications, regardless of the value of the debt. The reality however is that creditors chasing small debts through the county court are unlikely to take on the risk of failing to recover this additional cost.”<br /><br />Land Registry fees are also due to be increased this month. From 6 July, individual inspection and copy charges will increase by £1 or £2 and fixed fee applications will rise by up to £20.<br /><br /></p>
								
								
								<img src="../../content/cms/uploads/large/21253.jpg"  />
								
